I tracked it down to the reduce_operators function, seems that tokens and strings are being mixed up (there is no untokenize call, and out_tokens is not used) ?

Hi.  I'm working with angular2 and after some work I can download the file and save it, but file saved has the 00 byte interleaved when saved.

This is the code
####  the service
```
    downloadLogFile(id : string) {
      var headers = new Headers();
      headers.append('responseType', 'arraybuffer');
        return this.http.get('/runtime/getdevicelog/'+id,  { headers: headers })
                    .map( (res) => new Blob([res.arrayBuffer()], { type: "text/plain;charset=utf-8" }))
    };
```
#### the component
````
var reader = new FileReader();
this.runtimeService.downloadLogFile(id)
	.subscribe(
	 data => {
		reader.readAsArrayBuffer(data)
		console.log("download done")
	 },
	 err => {
	console.error(err)
	console.log("Error downloading the file.")
	 },
	  () => console.log('Completed file download.')
);
reader.onloadend = function (e) {
	var blob = new Blob([reader.result],{type:"text/plain;charset=utf-8"})
	saveAs(blob,id+".log",true);
}
 ````

The original text file has as first line this 
```
^[[34mINFO^[[0m[2016-11-27 18:10:50] Re Loading Indexed values in : linux_ports_3
