From what I can tell, Graphene does not support non-relay graphql queries (this is with SQLAlchemy).

To be concrete, the following works:
`    {
      allUsers {
        edges {
            node {
                id
                firstName
            }
        }
      }
    }
`

While this 
`{
      allUsers {
        id
        firstName
      }
    }`
Generates this error:
`[graphql.error.base.GraphQLError('Cannot query field "id" on type "UserDefaultConnection".')`

Did I miss a flag that enables non-relay graphql?

Say that I want to use variadic templates and parameter forwarding in factory method

```c++
class service {
private:
    service() = default;
    service( const service & o ) = default;
    service( std::vector<config_setting> c );
public:
    template<typename ... T>
    static shared_ptr<service> create( T&& ... all ) {
        return shared_ptr<service>( new service( std::forward<T>(all)... ) );
    }
```

How could I bind the constructor to the factory method?

I am doing something like:
```c++
py::class_<service, std::shared_ptr<service>>(m, "service")
.def(py::init(&service:create));
```

But it seems that I could not succesfully compile with error:

```
 cannot convert ‘& service::create’ (type ‘<unresolved overloaded function type>’) to type ‘std::vector<config_setting >&&’
```

Does anyone know how we could support case like this?

(Again a support-like question which probably roots in my rusty C/C++)

What is the most elegant way to access C-like "arrays" via pybind11?

For example there are two structs:

    typedef struct {
        int x;
        int y;
    } Point;

    typedef struct {
        Point* points;
        unsigned int size;
    } Path;

In C the user might do something like:

    Point points[2];
    Path path;
    path.size = 2;
    path.points = points;

Now I try to come up with an elegant way of wrapping this in pybind without too many custom getter/setter functions.

Ideally I would like a Python API like this:

    path = cmod.Path()
    path.points = [Point(), Point()]
    # maybe also path.size = 2

However a simple 

        .def_readwrite("points", &Path::points)

won't work. Is there a better way than doing the copying myself in a helper function?
